1
00:01:20,230 --> 00:0:22,505
Made By Chebo

2
00:01:58,230 --> 00:02:00,505
Quit eyeballing me, Flavius.

3
00:02:00,750 --> 00:02:03,822
I knew you when you was
a two-bit hustler on Bull Street.

4
00:02:49,030 --> 00:02:51,180
Excuse me!
Where can a fella get a cab?

5
00:02:51,430 --> 00:02:52,419
He just left.

6
00:02:52,670 --> 00:02:55,184
You can call the company, but I's you,
I'd wait on him to come back.

7
00:02:55,430 --> 00:02:57,068
'Less you want to take a ride.

8
00:02:57,310 --> 00:02:59,187
- You going to Jones Street?
- I'll get you there.

9
00:02:59,910 --> 00:03:01,184
Put your stuff in there.

10
00:03:06,190 --> 00:03:08,545
<i>To your right, Pirate's House...</i>

11
00:03:08,790 --> 00:03:11,065
<i>... built in 1794.</i>

12
00:03:11,310 --> 00:03:15,098
<i>All the ne'er-do-wells and scalawags</i>
<i>divided up their booty there.</i>

13
00:03:16,830 --> 00:03:19,025
<i>Sherman stayed</i>
<i>in the Green-Meldrim House...</i>

14
00:03:19,270 --> 00:03:22,068
<i>... to rest up</i>
<i>after his fiery march through Atlanta.</i>

15
00:03:22,310 --> 00:03:23,948
<i>He was going to burn Savannah...</i>

15
00:03:24,190 --> 00:03:27,182
<i>... but the locals drowned him</i>
<i>in Chatham Artillery punch...</i>

16
00:03:27,430 --> 00:03:29,739
<i>... and fancy parties</i>
<i>till he decided...</i>

17
00:03:29,990 --> 00:03:31,821
<i>... to spare our fair city.</i>

18
00:03:32,070 --> 00:03:34,300
<i>Forsyth Park, ladies and gentlemen.</i>

19
00:03:59,070 --> 00:04:00,503
You looking for something?

20
00:04:02,390 --> 00:04:03,345
No.

21
00:04:26,150 --> 00:04:27,265
Mr. Kelso?

22
00:04:27,510 --> 00:04:29,341
Are you Mr. Kelso?

23
00:04:29,670 --> 00:04:32,946
I'm Lorene Baxter.
Welcome to Savannah.

24
00:04:33,670 --> 00:04:36,867
<i>Town & Country</i>
is my favorite magazine.

25
00:04:37,390 --> 00:04:41,144
Oh, my land, where are my manners?
What can I get you to drink?

26
00:04:42,110 --> 00:04:43,828
Anything cold would be great.

27
00:04:49,870 --> 00:04:52,020
Mr. Williams restored this home.

28
00:04:52,270 --> 00:04:55,068
One of the many he saved
from the wrecking ball.

29
00:04:57,550 --> 00:05:00,269
The carriage house is reserved
for Jim's clients...

30
00:05:00,510 --> 00:05:02,944
...and guests, such as yourself.

31
00:05:13,230 --> 00:05:14,424
He's here.

32
00:05:17,230 --> 00:05:19,539
Welcome, Mr. Kelsy.

33
00:05:19,870 --> 00:05:22,623
- I'm sorry, Mr. Kelso?
- John Kelso.

34
00:05:22,870 --> 00:05:24,701
Yes. I'm Betty Harty.

35
00:05:24,950 --> 00:05:26,463
Sonny's been expecting you.

36
00:05:26,710 --> 00:05:28,621
I'm here to see Jim Williams.

37
00:05:28,870 --> 00:05:30,747
Sonny's Jim's attorney.

38
00:05:35,030 --> 00:05:36,304
Well, hell...

39
00:05:36,550 --> 00:05:37,869
...come on in, coach.

40
00:05:38,470 --> 00:05:39,425
John Kelso.

41
00:05:40,550 --> 00:05:43,587
Welcome to the old curiosity shop.
Take a seat.

42
00:05:51,950 --> 00:05:53,861
You let me know.

43
00:05:56,790 --> 00:05:58,985
- How was your trip?
- Fine. Mr. Williams said...

44
00:05:59,230 --> 00:06:03,189
He will be right along. We have
a little business to attend to first.

45
00:06:03,430 --> 00:06:06,900
Confidentiality agreement.
Just boilerplate stuff.

46
00:06:07,150 --> 00:06:08,469
Plus a paragraph...

47
00:06:08,750 --> 00:06:11,628
...outlining Jim's editorial privileges.

48
00:06:13,070 --> 00:06:17,222
<i>Town & Country</i> flew me down to write
a 500-word story on a Christmas party.

49
00:06:17,470 --> 00:06:20,064
It's a literary postcard.
Are you serious about this?

50
00:06:20,630 --> 00:06:22,302
It's not just any party.

51
00:06:24,310 --> 00:06:25,823
Have you asked the magazine?

52
00:06:26,070 --> 00:06:28,903
I'd rather have your word
than some New York lawyer.

53
00:06:30,630 --> 00:06:32,348
Be that as it may...

54
00:06:33,150 --> 00:06:34,868
...I'm not going to sign that.

55
00:06:36,070 --> 00:06:37,708
Damn! How come?

56
00:06:38,470 --> 00:06:40,381
It's just a little old party write-up.

57
00:06:40,830 --> 00:06:42,946
All the more reason
not to compromise my ethics.

58
00:06:43,190 --> 00:06:45,988
As a professional,
I'm sure you understand.

59
00:06:51,030 --> 00:06:52,429
Promise to be fair?

60
00:06:52,950 --> 00:06:54,668
Yes, of course.

61
00:07:02,870 --> 00:07:03,780
Jim...

62
00:07:05,270 --> 00:07:06,988
...this is John Kelso.

63
00:07:07,270 --> 00:07:08,305
Hello.

64
00:07:09,990 --> 00:07:12,060
Let's take a walk,
shall we, sport?

65
00:07:16,070 --> 00:07:18,220
We'll go around Forsyth Park.

66
00:07:29,510 --> 00:07:30,784
Would y'all mind...?

67
00:07:31,030 --> 00:07:32,668
Not at all, Betty.

68
00:07:33,710 --> 00:07:34,665
Come on.

69
00:07:41,910 --> 00:07:43,468
Did you sign Sonny's papers?

70
00:07:43,790 --> 00:07:44,905
Actually, no.

71
00:07:46,070 --> 00:07:50,029
Good for you. Sonny's
overly protective of my interests.

72
00:07:50,630 --> 00:07:52,780
- Still walking the dog, Mr. Glover?
- Yes, sir.

73
00:07:53,030 --> 00:07:55,385
Patrick do love his morning walk.

74
00:08:00,910 --> 00:08:03,982
Would you mind? Could I please have
my picture made with Uga?

75
00:08:04,390 --> 00:08:05,345
Great.

76
00:08:05,630 --> 00:08:06,665
Thanks.

77
00:08:08,470 --> 00:08:10,142
All right. Smile.

78
00:08:12,350 --> 00:08:14,068
Thanks. Dang good dog.

79
00:08:15,630 --> 00:08:16,540
Thank you very much.

80
00:08:16,830 --> 00:08:18,058
Thank you for asking.

81
00:08:19,510 --> 00:08:22,468
No matter what you and I ever do
in our lives, Mr. Kelso...

82
00:08:22,750 --> 00:08:24,866
...neither of us
will be as famous as Uga.

83
00:08:25,670 --> 00:08:26,739
He's the university mascot.

84
00:08:26,990 --> 00:08:28,821
- "The Georgia Bulldog."
- Is that right?

85
00:08:29,150 --> 00:08:33,063
I know I'm going to regret asking,
but that man said he was walking a dog.

86
00:08:34,950 --> 00:08:35,985
What dog?

87
00:08:36,270 --> 00:08:38,420
Mr. Glover was the law firm porter.

88
00:08:38,870 --> 00:08:42,988
Mr. Bouhan said in his will that
Mr. Glover should continue to be paid...

89
00:08:43,270 --> 00:08:46,387
...$ 15 every week for walking Patrick,
his Labrador.

90
00:08:46,710 --> 00:08:47,745
So...

91
00:08:48,590 --> 00:08:49,579
...where's Patrick?

92
00:08:49,870 --> 00:08:54,500
Patrick went on to his great rewards
2 years after Mr. Bouhan, about 1974.

93
00:08:54,790 --> 00:08:56,667
- The dog's dead.
- Quite.

94
00:08:57,750 --> 00:08:59,900
Why doesn't Mr. Glover walk Uga?

95
00:09:02,870 --> 00:09:04,747
Well, then, who'd walk Patrick?

96
00:09:08,430 --> 00:09:09,829
I see.

97
00:09:12,350 --> 00:09:14,306
- There it is.
- This is your house?

98
00:09:15,110 --> 00:09:19,069
Built by General Hugh Mercer in 1860,
but he never lived in this house.

99
00:09:19,350 --> 00:09:21,306
His great-grandson was Johnny Mercer.

100
00:09:21,590 --> 00:09:22,659
The songwriter?

101
00:09:22,950 --> 00:09:24,178
Savannah's own.

102
00:09:24,990 --> 00:09:26,821
What's your favorite of his tunes?

103
00:09:27,510 --> 00:09:30,388
My mother was always partial
to "Fools Rush In."

104
00:09:30,790 --> 00:09:31,939
Your mother.

105
00:09:32,750 --> 00:09:33,626
Indeed.

106
00:09:34,030 --> 00:09:38,820
I'd love to give you the grand tour, but
they're still setting up for the party.

107
00:09:39,750 --> 00:09:41,581
I thought the party was tomorrow night.

108
00:09:41,870 --> 00:09:43,349
There are two parties.

109
00:09:43,590 --> 00:09:46,548
Tonight is for bachelors.
Gentlemen only.

110
00:09:47,710 --> 00:09:48,825
Would you like to come?

111
00:09:49,990 --> 00:09:51,025
I'd like to cover it.

112
00:09:51,270 --> 00:09:54,421
I'm sorry. It's private.
Reporters aren't allowed.

113
00:09:54,670 --> 00:09:57,662
Would you like to see my shop?
It's back here in the carriage house.

114
00:10:00,150 --> 00:10:04,826
This house is one of the largest
in Savannah. It covers an entire block.

115
00:10:05,110 --> 00:10:06,463
It's right in here.

116
00:10:06,750 --> 00:10:08,581
This is where we do all of our...

117
00:10:08,830 --> 00:10:10,309
...restorations.

118
00:10:21,870 --> 00:10:23,701
This landscape, is it a Stubbs?

119
00:10:24,390 --> 00:10:25,539
Very good.

120
00:10:26,150 --> 00:10:27,583
My father was a dealer.

121
00:10:27,830 --> 00:10:30,867
It's called <i>Newmarket Heath</i>
<i>with a Rubbing-Down House.</i>

122
00:10:31,110 --> 00:10:33,783
It's a recent purchase I will unveil
at tomorrow night's event.

123
00:10:34,190 --> 00:10:35,703
It's an odd piece.

124
00:10:36,310 --> 00:10:38,028
The impasto is interesting.

125
00:10:39,070 --> 00:10:40,139
Where's your black light?

126
00:10:49,950 --> 00:10:50,905
It's an overpaint.

127
00:10:51,710 --> 00:10:53,382
Very good, sport.

128
00:10:57,710 --> 00:10:59,701
- You had it x-rayed yet?
- No.

129
00:11:00,630 --> 00:11:02,382
How will you know
what it's obscuring?

130
00:11:04,190 --> 00:11:06,021
I rather enjoy not knowing.

131
00:12:02,150 --> 00:12:03,344
Just a minute.

132
00:12:11,190 --> 00:12:12,828
- Who is it?
- Mandy.

133
00:12:13,110 --> 00:12:13,986
Who?

134
00:12:15,870 --> 00:12:17,019
I don't know a Mandy.

135
00:12:17,270 --> 00:12:19,738
Of course not.
You won't open the damn door.

136
00:12:21,430 --> 00:12:23,307
Hi. Nice to meet you.

137
00:12:31,790 --> 00:12:33,701
You all got some ice?

138
00:12:35,990 --> 00:12:37,309
Sure, help yourself.

139
00:12:37,790 --> 00:12:40,862
Joe Odom's fridge is on the blink.
And plus, at present...

140
00:12:41,110 --> 00:12:43,180
...we don't have electricity.

141
00:12:45,110 --> 00:12:46,384
Thirsty?

142
00:12:47,430 --> 00:12:49,580
Me? No.
No, not really.

143
00:12:51,350 --> 00:12:55,343
If you're thirsty, a drink'll cure it.
If you're not, a drink'll prevent it.

144
00:12:55,630 --> 00:12:57,939
Prevention is better than a cure.

145
00:13:00,790 --> 00:13:02,746
Put on some pants, John Kelso.

146
00:13:05,270 --> 00:13:06,783
Sure, just let me get a pair.

147
00:13:09,590 --> 00:13:12,468
This is our newest addition
to the Odom House.

148
00:13:12,790 --> 00:13:16,100
As you see, Joe's been creative
with our electrical dilemma.

149
00:13:18,590 --> 00:13:22,219
I done this before
and I ain't never been killed yet.

150
00:13:22,470 --> 00:13:24,859
But there's a first time for everything.

151
00:13:32,270 --> 00:13:33,146
There we go!

152
00:13:33,390 --> 00:13:34,584
We got it!

153
00:13:35,790 --> 00:13:36,700
No problem.

154
00:13:37,150 --> 00:13:38,219
Joe Odom?

155
00:13:38,470 --> 00:13:39,698
The one, the only.

156
00:13:40,070 --> 00:13:41,423
Where's my libation?

157
00:13:41,710 --> 00:13:42,540
Hold these.

158
00:13:44,270 --> 00:13:46,465
To Savannah Electric and Power!

159
00:13:47,110 --> 00:13:49,419
And let's not forget our friends...

160
00:13:49,990 --> 00:13:50,900
...the...

161
00:13:51,350 --> 00:13:52,066
...whoever!

162
00:13:53,590 --> 00:13:55,899
Here's to you!
All right, inside.

163
00:13:56,910 --> 00:14:01,267
Honey, that's a tough job,
but you're talking to the lady. Hello!

164
00:14:02,310 --> 00:14:05,143
Have you met Mr. Kelso,
our newest addition to Savannah?

165
00:14:05,430 --> 00:14:06,749
Jerry Spence.

166
00:14:06,990 --> 00:14:08,708
- How are you?
- I'm charmed now.

167
00:14:08,990 --> 00:14:11,106
- How are you?
- I'm pretty good.

168
00:14:11,350 --> 00:14:13,466
- I wonder if he goes to my church?
- I wonder.

169
00:14:13,790 --> 00:14:14,779
Episcopalian.

170
00:14:15,030 --> 00:14:16,224
We'll find out.

171
00:14:16,470 --> 00:14:17,698
<i>Sanitation</i>

172
00:14:18,310 --> 00:14:20,870
<i>I see all night long</i>
<i>Hauling in great big cans</i>

173
00:14:23,150 --> 00:14:26,381
<i>I'm hoping one day soon</i>
<i>She'll let me be a Hefty man</i>

174
00:14:27,830 --> 00:14:30,219
<i>In the Dumpster</i>
<i>We'll be making love</i>

175
00:14:30,470 --> 00:14:32,620
<i>In the Dumpster</i>
<i>Beneath the stars above</i>

176
00:14:32,950 --> 00:14:35,305
<i>In the Dumpster</i>
<i>I smell paradise</i>

177
00:14:35,590 --> 00:14:37,421
<i>Don 't have to ask me twice</i>

178
00:14:37,710 --> 00:14:39,666
<i>It's all I'm thinking of</i>

179
00:14:39,910 --> 00:14:42,470
<i>Just me and that trash girl</i>
<i>Making that Dumpster love</i>

180
00:14:54,710 --> 00:14:55,586
Do you like that?

181
00:14:55,830 --> 00:14:56,979
Strong.

182
00:14:57,350 --> 00:15:00,023
Strong and good.
Chatham Artillery punch.

183
00:15:00,310 --> 00:15:01,265
What's in it?

184
00:15:01,510 --> 00:15:03,228
3 parts fruit, 7 parts liquor.

185
00:15:03,510 --> 00:15:05,466
Whatever's available on both counts.

186
00:15:05,790 --> 00:15:07,428
Great party. Great house.

187
00:15:08,470 --> 00:15:12,827
The fella that owns it is in Europe
for a year. Asked me to look in on it.

188
00:15:13,110 --> 00:15:14,429
Water the plants.

189
00:15:17,710 --> 00:15:18,506
Squatting?

190
00:15:19,870 --> 00:15:21,622
That's a vicious word.

191
00:15:21,950 --> 00:15:23,588
You're not a lawyer, are you?

192
00:15:25,270 --> 00:15:28,342
Good. They're the scum of the earth.
And I should know...

193
00:15:28,630 --> 00:15:31,190
...being an ex-barrister myself.

194
00:15:31,590 --> 00:15:32,545
Ex?

195
00:15:33,190 --> 00:15:36,341
Ceremoniously disbarred
not two years ago.

196
00:15:36,630 --> 00:15:38,507
Had a little accounting snafu.

197
00:15:39,110 --> 00:15:40,338
What do you do now?

198
00:15:40,590 --> 00:15:43,388
Me and Mandy,
we're going to open a piano bar.

199
00:15:43,710 --> 00:15:44,745
You already have one.

200
00:15:44,990 --> 00:15:46,469
Looks that way, doesn't it?

201
00:15:46,990 --> 00:15:49,140
Wait a minute. Hold the music.

202
00:15:49,430 --> 00:15:50,306
Look.

203
00:15:52,230 --> 00:15:53,458
Look at this.

204
00:15:53,790 --> 00:15:54,859
Jerry Spence.

205
00:15:56,030 --> 00:15:58,749
You have outdone yourself again.

206
00:15:58,990 --> 00:16:02,585
That is a coif definitely befitting
your stature as the future ex...

207
00:16:02,910 --> 00:16:04,309
...Mrs. Joe Odom.

208
00:16:05,030 --> 00:16:06,748
Keep dreaming, darling.

209
00:16:07,150 --> 00:16:08,344
You're in love.

210
00:16:11,950 --> 00:16:13,941
She is one beautiful woman.

211
00:16:14,310 --> 00:16:15,709
You two engaged?

212
00:16:16,910 --> 00:16:17,979
Not yet.

213
00:16:19,710 --> 00:16:22,782
It's getting late. I'm going to
hit the road. Nice meeting you.

214
00:16:23,030 --> 00:16:24,383
No, wait a minute.

215
00:16:25,270 --> 00:16:26,908
Joe's rule #2:

216
00:16:27,190 --> 00:16:31,183
If you have to leave a party,
you always take a traveler.

217
00:16:32,150 --> 00:16:34,539
I can live with that one.
Nice to meet you.

218
00:16:41,870 --> 00:16:42,859
Hey, there.

219
00:16:43,790 --> 00:16:46,304
Better to be on the edge of a party,
don't you think?

220
00:16:48,550 --> 00:16:49,824
Thanks for inviting me.

221
00:16:50,070 --> 00:16:51,105
Anytime.

222
00:16:51,350 --> 00:16:52,624
Every time.

223
00:16:59,030 --> 00:17:00,145
Earlier...

224
00:17:00,390 --> 00:17:01,709
...how'd you know my name?

225
00:17:01,990 --> 00:17:03,582
Welcome to Savannah.

226
00:17:11,350 --> 00:17:12,465
Mr. John Kelso?

227
00:17:14,550 --> 00:17:15,505
This is for you.

228
00:17:23,510 --> 00:17:26,820
<i>I'm not in. Leave a message</i>
<i>and I'll get back to you.</i>

229
00:17:46,950 --> 00:17:48,508
- Mr. Kelso?
- Yes.

230
00:17:48,750 --> 00:17:51,344
I'm Lucille Wright.
I cater Mr. Williams' parties.

231
00:17:51,590 --> 00:17:53,308
- Nice to meet you.
- He'll be down shortly.

232
00:17:53,550 --> 00:17:55,302
Would you like to see what we'll serve?

233
00:17:55,550 --> 00:17:56,744
Of course.

234
00:17:56,990 --> 00:17:58,059
Come in.

235
00:18:00,350 --> 00:18:02,625
Lots of fresh vegetables...

236
00:18:02,870 --> 00:18:04,428
...hot bread...

237
00:18:04,670 --> 00:18:06,069
...jumbo shrimp.

238
00:18:07,670 --> 00:18:10,264
Let's see.
This is smoked ham and turkey.

239
00:18:10,870 --> 00:18:11,586
Both.

240
00:18:11,830 --> 00:18:15,789
A big fruit platter.
And this is a wonderful crab dish.

241
00:18:16,030 --> 00:18:16,940
A bisque?

242
00:18:17,510 --> 00:18:18,260
Jeff Braswell.

243
00:18:19,870 --> 00:18:23,146
- I shoot Jim's parties.
- Let's get a shot of the whole spread.

244
00:18:23,390 --> 00:18:25,779
<i>Town & Country</i>
loves its pretty pictures.

245
00:18:26,270 --> 00:18:28,226
And pumpkin cornbread.

246
00:18:29,590 --> 00:18:33,139
Mr. Williams insists on
low-country cooking for his parties.

247
00:18:33,630 --> 00:18:36,428
Oh, you're going to have fun tonight.

248
00:18:36,670 --> 00:18:38,422
Indeed he is, Lucille.

249
00:18:39,550 --> 00:18:41,859
Good fit. 44 long.

250
00:18:45,470 --> 00:18:47,745
I have an eye for framing things.

251
00:18:50,070 --> 00:18:52,061
Welcome to Mercer House, Mr. Kelso.

252
00:18:52,990 --> 00:18:55,379
You have outdone yourself again
this year.

253
00:18:55,630 --> 00:18:57,109
