01:11:56,590 --> 01:12:01,220
Gunshot residue test is unreliable.
It's inadmissable in some jurisdictions.

1004
01:12:01,470 --> 01:12:04,906
Finley's got Doc Poe. We will counter
with cutting-edge science...

1005
01:12:05,150 --> 01:12:07,539
...with an expert we got from up north.

1006
01:12:09,390 --> 01:12:12,462
They say the scene was contrived.
What do you say?

1007
01:12:12,830 --> 01:12:14,263
That's our silver bullet.

1008
01:12:15,190 --> 01:12:16,862
Shoddy police work.

1009
01:12:17,110 --> 01:12:18,623
Take a look at this.

1010
01:12:25,230 --> 01:12:26,583
That's me!

1011
01:12:26,830 --> 01:12:28,183
Just like you said.

1012
01:12:28,430 --> 01:12:30,864
Ground zero.
Cops should never have let you in.

1013
01:12:31,990 --> 01:12:34,709
I kind of let myself in
through the back gate.

1014
01:12:35,990 --> 01:12:38,106
They shouldn't have let you get in.

1015
01:12:39,670 --> 01:12:41,945
<i>Happy together</i>

1016
01:12:42,750 --> 01:12:45,184
<i>Unhappy together</i>

1017
01:12:45,950 --> 01:12:48,145
<i>And won 't it be fine</i>

1018
01:12:53,230 --> 01:12:56,267
<i>Days may be cloudy or sunny</i>

1019
01:12:59,310 --> 01:13:02,939
<i>We're in or we're out of the money</i>

1020
01:13:07,070 --> 01:13:08,981
<i>But I'm with you always</i>

1021
01:13:11,030 --> 01:13:12,941
<i>Come rain or</i>

1022
01:13:14,910 --> 01:13:16,821
<i>Shine</i>

1023
01:13:27,470 --> 01:13:28,664
Joe Odom.

1024
01:13:32,430 --> 01:13:34,421
You're good.
I didn't know you sang.

1025
01:13:34,670 --> 01:13:36,023
- You never asked.
- How you doing?

1026
01:13:36,270 --> 01:13:37,498
Good, how are you?

1027
01:13:38,150 --> 01:13:41,347
- You got another set?
- No, me and Joe's just sitting in.

1028
01:13:41,590 --> 01:13:42,864
Want to get a cup of coffee?

1029
01:13:43,110 --> 01:13:44,862
Business or pleasure?

1030
01:13:45,230 --> 01:13:46,219
Come on.

1031
01:13:48,870 --> 01:13:53,421
Normally, there'd be no problem.
The general rule is rich people get off.

1032
01:13:53,670 --> 01:13:55,581
Problem is, they're usually straight.

1033
01:13:55,870 --> 01:13:57,940
See, so it's a volatile issue.

1034
01:13:58,190 --> 01:14:00,624
- I'm not crazy?
- No. Neither is Sonny.

1035
01:14:00,870 --> 01:14:02,667
Jim's friends knew he was gay.

1036
01:14:02,910 --> 01:14:06,698
Secretly, they congratulated themselves
on being so cosmopolitan.

1037
01:14:06,950 --> 01:14:11,660
If they knew he was completely open with
his sexuality, they'd have shunned him.

1038
01:14:12,110 --> 01:14:13,862
Maybe the jury will too.

1039
01:14:14,110 --> 01:14:14,986
You think?

1040
01:14:16,830 --> 01:14:19,981
Of course, no one'll ever really know
what happened that night.

1041
01:14:20,230 --> 01:14:22,983
But Jim's told the story
a thousand times, never wavered.

1042
01:14:23,230 --> 01:14:24,902
You're quite the advocate.

1043
01:14:25,150 --> 01:14:28,779
What happened to
"Stick around and stay objective"?

1044
01:14:29,030 --> 01:14:32,625
Objectively, it's looking like
they'll hang him for his sexuality.

1045
01:14:32,870 --> 01:14:35,464
Something that would never happen
in New York, right?

1046
01:14:36,830 --> 01:14:39,105
Well, you said it, not me.

1047
01:14:41,230 --> 01:14:42,902
You don't seem like you're from here.

1048
01:14:43,150 --> 01:14:45,584
I was born here, didn't like it...

1049
01:14:45,830 --> 01:14:46,945
...moved away.

1050
01:14:47,190 --> 01:14:49,260
Figured out the part
I didn't like was me.

1051
01:14:49,510 --> 01:14:52,308
So I worked on that,
and I moved back.

1052
01:14:54,310 --> 01:14:55,902
I got my first kiss right here.

1053
01:14:56,150 --> 01:14:58,584
Sammy Jenks.
Gave him a black eye.

1054
01:14:58,830 --> 01:15:00,548
You did? How hard?

1055
01:15:03,190 --> 01:15:04,623
That's what love'll do.

1056
01:15:05,110 --> 01:15:09,581
I have trouble picturing what kind of
woman you'd take the trouble to marry.

1057
01:15:12,990 --> 01:15:14,628
First love situation.

1058
01:15:15,270 --> 01:15:19,343
We got married a week after graduating
college, if you can believe that.

1059
01:15:19,590 --> 01:15:20,818
So what happened?

1060
01:15:21,070 --> 01:15:22,662
You want to hear my sob story?

1061
01:15:22,910 --> 01:15:26,141
I think she thought
she was marrying Norman Mailer.

1062
01:15:26,990 --> 01:15:28,662
She thought I'd be famous.

1063
01:15:29,230 --> 01:15:33,701
After the book was published, she'd wake
up at the crack of dawn on Sunday...

1064
01:15:33,950 --> 01:15:36,180
...make coffee, cross her fingers...

1065
01:15:36,430 --> 01:15:39,581
...and look in that Sunday <i>Times,</i>
sure it was going to be a bestseller.

1066
01:15:39,950 --> 01:15:43,989
One Sunday, she didn't wake up early,
didn't make coffee...

1067
01:15:44,230 --> 01:15:46,061
...didn't cross her fingers...

1068
01:15:47,230 --> 01:15:48,424
...and I knew.

1069
01:15:49,470 --> 01:15:52,143
She left you
because your book wasn't a hit?

1070
01:15:52,910 --> 01:15:56,380
I don't know, Kelso.
It seems pretty shallow to me.

1071
01:15:58,430 --> 01:16:00,102
What about you and Joe Odom?

1072
01:16:01,110 --> 01:16:02,509
Me and Joe.

1073
01:16:02,750 --> 01:16:04,388
We're just friends.

1074
01:16:04,750 --> 01:16:07,264
We have a real musical relationship.

1075
01:16:07,830 --> 01:16:11,027
We're like the Steve and Eydie
of Savannah.

1076
01:16:16,510 --> 01:16:18,262
My God, it's quiet.

1077
01:16:18,630 --> 01:16:19,540
Too quiet.

1078
01:16:19,790 --> 01:16:22,304
Joe'll be playing at that bar
until dawn.

1079
01:16:27,470 --> 01:16:28,903
I should probably go.

1080
01:16:35,110 --> 01:16:39,388
In case you're wondering,
this is the perfect time for a kiss.

1081
01:16:40,710 --> 01:16:42,780
Sammy Jenks warned me about you.

1082
01:17:02,310 --> 01:17:03,379
Good night.

1083
01:17:10,670 --> 01:17:14,299
Ladies and gentlemen,
you constitute our jury for this trial.

1084
01:17:14,550 --> 01:17:16,302
It's expected to last several days.

1085
01:17:16,550 --> 01:17:18,222
I'll let you go home for the evening...

1086
01:17:18,470 --> 01:17:22,509
...instruct you to be back
in the morning at 9:30 in the jury room.

1087
01:17:22,750 --> 01:17:25,503
If anybody tries to approach you
about this case...

1088
01:17:25,750 --> 01:17:28,218
...report it to me
the first thing in the morning.

1089
01:17:28,790 --> 01:17:30,667
You're excused for the evening.

1090
01:17:33,550 --> 01:17:36,064
Mr. Driggers, let me speak to you.

1091
01:17:41,750 --> 01:17:43,422
Luther, listen.

1092
01:17:43,670 --> 01:17:46,980
This is a courtroom. Don't bring
those flies in here tomorrow.

1093
01:17:47,310 --> 01:17:51,940
And leave that vial of water,
or whatever that stuff is, at home.

1094
01:17:52,550 --> 01:17:53,699
Sam...

1095
01:17:54,030 --> 01:17:58,023
...you know, when we were in Georgia,
I know how you hated my bugs...

1096
01:17:58,270 --> 01:17:59,988
...and you know how I love them.

1097
01:18:00,590 --> 01:18:02,945
We're no longer at the university.
This is a courtroom.

1098
01:18:03,190 --> 01:18:06,660
I'm telling you to leave
all that foolishness at home.

1099
01:18:07,670 --> 01:18:09,706
I do take umbrage.

1100
01:18:10,190 --> 01:18:11,669
But I'll do it.

1101
01:18:12,790 --> 01:18:15,350
What is the story with the guy
with the horsefly epaulets?

1102
01:18:15,590 --> 01:18:17,023
Luther Driggers.

1103
01:18:17,270 --> 01:18:18,464
He's a genius.

1104
01:18:18,710 --> 01:18:20,701
Developed the "No-Bug" strip.

1105
01:18:20,950 --> 01:18:23,703
The company he worked for
took the credit and the money.

1106
01:18:23,950 --> 01:18:27,101
Now he just wanders around town
with a bottle of poison in his pocket.

1107
01:18:27,350 --> 01:18:28,226
Of course.

1108
01:18:28,470 --> 01:18:32,145
Says someday he's going to put it
in the water supply, do us all in.

1109
01:18:32,390 --> 01:18:34,062
Why do you want him on the jury?

1110
01:18:34,310 --> 01:18:37,347
We're the defense team.
We need all the nuts we can get.

1111
01:18:37,590 --> 01:18:38,989
What about Largent?

1112
01:18:39,310 --> 01:18:41,380
Finley's up for reelection.

1113
01:18:41,750 --> 01:18:43,024
If he strikes Luther...

1114
01:18:43,270 --> 01:18:44,908
...he might upset him enough to...

1115
01:18:45,750 --> 01:18:46,705
...you know...

1116
01:18:48,790 --> 01:18:50,701
I'll be back in on Sunday.

1117
01:18:51,470 --> 01:18:54,701
You've got a murder trial
starting in 3 days. Where you going?

1118
01:18:56,950 --> 01:18:58,986
Home opener against 'Bama.

1119
01:19:00,910 --> 01:19:02,343
Go, Dogs!

1120
01:19:05,190 --> 01:19:06,145
Is he really leaving?

1121
01:19:06,390 --> 01:19:08,108
Oh, yeah.
Better say a prayer.

1122
01:19:10,310 --> 01:19:11,584
All right, Mr. Largent...

1123
01:19:11,830 --> 01:19:15,266
...the state has the burden of proof,
and you have the opening.

1124
01:19:18,350 --> 01:19:19,419
Your Honor.

1125
01:19:22,790 --> 01:19:25,543
Good morning, Your Honor,
ladies and gentlemen of the jury.

1126
01:19:27,430 --> 01:19:30,820
The state of Georgia is ready
and most anxious to proceed.

1127
01:19:40,390 --> 01:19:42,028
If the court pleases.

1128
01:19:53,870 --> 01:19:56,225
The philosopher Thomas Hobbes
is quoted as saying...

1129
01:19:56,470 --> 01:19:57,869
...that life is...

1130
01:19:58,110 --> 01:19:59,941
...nasty, brutish...

1131
01:20:00,550 --> 01:20:01,744
...and short.

1132
01:20:03,470 --> 01:20:06,667
And surely it must have seemed so
to Billy Hanson...

1133
01:20:07,430 --> 01:20:09,182
...as he lay wounded...

1134
01:20:09,550 --> 01:20:11,859
...his blood and his life...

1135
01:20:12,110 --> 01:20:15,307
...oozing out
onto Jim Williams' Persian rug.

1136
01:20:17,550 --> 01:20:20,269
It's important for you to know
that the defendant...

1137
01:20:22,590 --> 01:20:24,342
By the end of this trial...

1138
01:20:24,870 --> 01:20:25,859
...I believe...

1139
01:20:26,590 --> 01:20:29,309
...that when faced with the evidence...

1140
01:20:29,830 --> 01:20:31,024
...you will render...

1141
01:20:31,270 --> 01:20:34,103
...the verdict that is fair and just:

1142
01:20:36,710 --> 01:20:38,905
Guilty of first-degree murder.

1143
01:20:44,190 --> 01:20:45,225
Thank you.

1144
01:20:54,430 --> 01:20:58,628
All right, Mr. Seiler,
we've been going for some time now.

1145
01:20:58,870 --> 01:21:02,385
Would you prefer to make
your opening statement after recess?

1146
01:21:05,470 --> 01:21:08,701
I would prefer to address
the jury now, Your Honor.

1147
01:21:11,550 --> 01:21:13,666
What I have to say won't take long.

1148
01:21:17,430 --> 01:21:19,466
I apologize if I look tired...

1149
01:21:20,750 --> 01:21:22,547
...if my eyes are red...

1150
01:21:23,270 --> 01:21:25,340
...if my complexion is sallow.

1151
01:21:26,110 --> 01:21:28,180
But I came by it honestly.

1152
01:21:29,270 --> 01:21:30,498
Because...

1153
01:21:30,750 --> 01:21:32,945
...I have not had much sleep lately.

1154
01:21:33,470 --> 01:21:35,745
For while my bed is soft...

1155
01:21:36,590 --> 01:21:38,785
...my client's is not.

1156
01:21:39,390 --> 01:21:42,666
And while I'm surrounded
by my loving family...

1157
01:21:43,630 --> 01:21:45,143
...Jim Williams...

1158
01:21:45,910 --> 01:21:47,229
...my friend...

1159
01:21:47,830 --> 01:21:49,058
...my client...

1160
01:21:50,350 --> 01:21:51,863
...is locked up in a room...

1161
01:21:52,110 --> 01:21:55,386
...full of thieves,
murderers and rapists.

1162
01:21:58,630 --> 01:22:00,143
You're the ones I want.

1163
01:22:01,030 --> 01:22:03,021
You're the ones I trust.

1164
01:22:04,390 --> 01:22:08,542
Because although it is Jim Williams
on trial here today...

1165
01:22:08,990 --> 01:22:11,504
...when I look at the circumstances...

1166
01:22:11,830 --> 01:22:13,502
...I think to myself...

1167
01:22:13,870 --> 01:22:14,825
...there...

1168
01:22:15,070 --> 01:22:17,868
...but for the grace of God,
go you...

1169
01:22:18,230 --> 01:22:19,185
...or I.

1170
01:22:19,870 --> 01:22:22,623
You know why?
Because I guaran-damn-tee you:

1171
01:22:22,870 --> 01:22:25,828
Someone comes into my home
and shoot at me, I will shoot back.

1172
01:22:26,070 --> 01:22:28,265
And I'll shoot back again and again...

1173
01:22:28,510 --> 01:22:31,024
...and again,
until I'm sure that they're dead.

1174
01:22:31,270 --> 01:22:35,502
Until I'm sure that my home
and my family are safe.

1175
01:22:39,990 --> 01:22:41,139
And then...

1176
01:22:41,910 --> 01:22:43,821
...old Finley here, my friend...

1177
01:22:44,470 --> 01:22:46,381
...would be prosecuting me.

1178
01:22:46,750 --> 01:22:48,547
I'd be the one on trial.

1179
01:22:49,110 --> 01:22:50,509
And my life...

1180
01:22:50,750 --> 01:22:52,149
...would be in the hands...

1181
01:22:52,790 --> 01:22:55,065
...of good folks like you.

1182
01:22:55,190 --> 01:22:57,226
He is way out-of-bounds.

1183
01:22:57,750 --> 01:23:01,584
He didn't object once during ours.
We'll look like assholes.

1184
01:23:01,830 --> 01:23:03,741
Folks not swayed by fancy words.

1185
01:23:04,430 --> 01:23:06,739
Folks who would not be prejudiced...

1186
01:23:07,830 --> 01:23:10,105
...who would not judge a man...

1187
01:23:10,350 --> 01:23:12,261
...by the color of his skin...

1188
01:23:12,870 --> 01:23:15,020
...or the amount of money that he makes.

1189
01:23:15,390 --> 01:23:16,539
I will say...

1190
01:23:17,150 --> 01:23:19,141
...the simple fact of the matter...

1191
01:23:19,390 --> 01:23:20,505
...is...

1192
01:23:21,310 --> 01:23:22,982
...Jim Williams...

1193
01:23:23,910 --> 01:23:25,901
...murdered no one.

1194
01:23:30,030 --> 01:23:32,624
How did you think it went?
Because I was very pleased.

1195
01:23:32,870 --> 01:23:35,828
Sonny has a certain style,
a flair, doesn't he?

1196
01:23:36,070 --> 01:23:37,219
From what I've seen...

1197
01:23:37,470 --> 01:23:40,348
...that man could weave horseshit
into Egyptian cotton.

1198
01:23:40,750 --> 01:23:42,706
Pleasantly surprised.

1199
01:23:43,750 --> 01:23:45,945
John Kelso,
I hope you understand.

1200
01:23:46,350 --> 01:23:48,181
Might I consider you my friend?

1201
01:23:49,750 --> 01:23:50,785
Yes.

1202
01:23:54,670 --> 01:23:58,504
The lack of gunshot residue in the hand,
plus the other things I mentioned...

1203
01:23:58,750 --> 01:24:01,503
...led me to the conclusion
that the scene was contrived.

1204
01:24:03,830 --> 01:24:05,548
Thank you, Detective Boone.

1205
01:24:05,790 --> 01:24:07,269
No further questions.

1206
01:24:09,870 --> 01:24:11,269
Detective...

1207
01:24:12,670 --> 01:24:15,867
...I'd like to revisit
some of the things...

1208
01:24:16,470 --> 01:24:18,984
...you said just then in direct.

1209
01:24:22,150 --> 01:24:25,984
You testified there was blood
on Hanson's hand, correct?

1210
01:24:26,230 --> 01:24:29,540
Yes. There was blood in the palm
of the victim's hand.

1211
01:24:30,030 --> 01:24:33,306
And that's important because if Hanson
had been holding the gun...

1212
01:24:33,550 --> 01:24:34,869
...there'd be no blood.

1213
01:24:36,990 --> 01:24:40,426
But you never saw the blood
on the victim's hand, did you?

1214
01:24:40,790 --> 01:24:41,745
No.

1215
01:24:42,750 --> 01:24:45,139
The blood was noted
in the autopsy report.

1216
01:24:45,390 --> 01:24:47,745
I didn't turn them over
when I bagged them.

1217
01:24:48,430 --> 01:24:50,785
I believe you also testified that...

1218
01:24:51,030 --> 01:24:55,706
...you believe the final shot was fired
from above the victim, is that correct?

1219
01:24:56,470 --> 01:25:00,463
I concluded that the shot came
from someone standing over the victim...

1220
01:25:00,790 --> 01:25:02,109
...execution style.

1221
01:25:04,590 --> 01:25:06,103
A <i>coup de grâce.</i>

1222
01:25:06,710 --> 01:25:08,143
A <i>coup de grâce?</i>

1223
01:25:15,510 --> 01:25:17,785
Will you tell the jury, please...

1224
01:25:18,750 --> 01:25:22,584
...did you find Jim's prints
on Billy's gun?

1225
01:25:26,230 --> 01:25:29,381
The Luger handle has a textured surface.

1226
01:25:30,990 --> 01:25:33,026
Is the answer no, Detective?

1227
01:25:33,990 --> 01:25:36,550
Yes, the answer was no.

1228
01:25:36,790 --> 01:25:38,667
Yes, the answer is no.

1229
01:25:40,070 --> 01:25:42,061
State's 22, Your Honor.

1230
01:25:46,070 --> 01:25:47,981
Who's this handsome fellow?

1231
01:25:48,270 --> 01:25:49,225
That's me.

1232
01:25:52,190 --> 01:25:53,703
Who's this?

1233
01:25:55,150 --> 01:25:57,710
That's that reporter fella
from up north.

1234
01:25:57,950 --> 01:26:00,180
The one that's working with Williams.

1235
01:26:00,790 --> 01:26:02,508
I don't know how he got in.

1236
01:26:02,950 --> 01:26:04,303
And this?

1237
01:26:05,110 --> 01:26:06,463
Young officer...

1238
01:26:06,710 --> 01:26:08,109
...name escapes me.

1239
01:26:08,350 --> 01:26:12,901
Understandable. You'd need a program
to keep track of everyone in that room.

1240
01:26:13,150 --> 01:26:14,344
Objection!

1241
01:26:14,590 --> 01:26:16,387
Counsel's testifying.

1242
01:26:16,790 --> 01:26:18,109
Strike that.

1243
01:26:18,750 --> 01:26:21,344
I would much rather have
the detective tell us.

1244
01:26:21,670 --> 01:26:24,025
How many people was in that room?

1245
01:26:25,390 --> 01:26:26,584
Seven.

1246
01:26:27,470 --> 01:26:28,459
No, eight.

1247
01:26:28,710 --> 01:26:31,782
"Seven, no, eight."
And a pussycat.

1248
01:26:34,990 --> 01:26:36,742
Read the funny papers, Detective?

1249
01:26:37,390 --> 01:26:38,709
Not often.

1250
01:26:39,310 --> 01:26:42,268
In the funny papers they sometimes
have this little competition...

1251
01:26:42,510 --> 01:26:44,705
